Project Linear Regression: Boston House Price Prediction¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on Linear Regression. We will use the Boston house price data for the exercise.

Problem Statement¶

The problem on hand is to predict the housing prices of a town or a suburb based on the features of the locality provided to us. In the process, we need to identify the most important features in the dataset. We need to employ techniques of data preprocessing and build a linear regression model that predicts the prices for us.

Data Information¶

Each record in the database describes a Boston suburb or town. The data was drawn from the Boston Standard Metropolitan Statistical Area (SMSA) in 1970. Detailed attribute information can be found below-

Attribute Information (in order):

  • CRIM: per capita crime rate by town
  • ZN: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • INDUS: proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • NOX: nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • RM: average number of rooms per dwelling
  • AGE: proportion of owner-occupied units built before 1940
  • DIS: weighted distances to five Boston employment centers
  • RAD: index of accessibility to radial highways
  • TAX: full-value property-tax rate per 10,000 dollars
  • PTRATIO: pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • LSTAT: %lower status of the population
  • MEDV: Median value of owner-occupied homes in 1000 dollars

Observations:

  • Per Capita Crime Rate has some outliers in the high end: 75th percentile is 3.66 per capita town rate, while max is 88.976 (which, in this context, is absurdly high and represents a very dangerous town). These outliers seem to have a big effect on the standard deviation and mean, which would otherwise be smaller (IQR has a smaller range, with 75th percentile being at 3.6, 25th percentile at 0.08 and mean at 3.6). Aside from this outlier observation, it seems that the top 25% CRIM rates are a lot higher in general: the bottom 50% are below .26, and that ramps up to 3.67 for 75th percentile. Only a few towns are very dangerous, while most aren't close to them.
  • ZN has an interesting distribution. Up to 50% of the houses have no proportion zoned for lots (0). Afterwardsm the 75th percentile has 12.5 and the max is 100. This can be explained because most of the plots are not over 25,000 sq ft, and ZN only has a proportion value for plots over 25,000 sq ft. This column will have a positive skew, but that will be explored afterwards in the univariate analysis.
  • INDUS explains the proportion of non-retail business acres per town. This will also have highly different values depending on the town. Because of this, the range is wide, as expected. With minimums of 0.46 in towns which don't have a lot of non-retail business acres, up to 27.74 acres in towns which do. In this column, the values seem to have a more even distribution: they ramp up from 0.46 to 5.19 in the 25th percentile, then 9.69 in the 50th, 18.1 in 75th and finally 27.74 at max. Values don't seem to have as many outliers, the mean and std deviation represent this.
  • CHAS is a dummy variable which is either 0 or 1. The mean in 0.07 and the std deviation is 0.25, which means most values are 0 and only a few are 1. When we see the percentiles this can be confirmed: values are 0 up to the 75th percentile.
  • NOX has a very small range, which makes sense because it explains the nitric oxides concentration parts per 10 mllion, and higher values than those presented would not make sense unless extreme air pollution.
  • Rooms per dwelling has a marked difference between households, with the lowest 25% at only 5.8 rooms and the highest at 8.78 rooms. Even the minimum is at 3.56, even the zones with the lowest values in RM have a close to 4 rooms per household on average. The standard deviation is really low, and the mean coincides almost perfectly with the 50th percentile. This means that RM most likely has a normal distribution and few (if any) outliers which heavily skew the data.
  • AGE is different from the last column discussed. It has a very wide range: minimum at 2.9 and maximum at 100. It seems that this minimum value is an outlier, as the quarter percentiles (25th, 50th 75th and max) ramp up quickly from this minimum, until it reaches 100 as maximum. From this, we can infer that a lot of towns have a high proportion of owner-occupied units built before 1940.
  • DIS seems to have an outlier in the maximum value, the distance between minimum, 25th percentile, 50th percentile and 75th is pretty similar: ramping up from 1.12 to 5.18. And then the maximum value is 12.1265. Despite this value, the standard deviation is still 2.1 and the mean is 3.79, these outliers do affect the stats but not as much as in other cases (like CRIM). Most towns have a similar weighted distance to five Boston employment centers.
  • The accessibility to Radial Highways has the same value (24) in the 75th percentile and the max: a lot of the towns have a high accessibility index to these highways. The lowest values (from minimum to 50th percentile) have a range of 1 to 5: most towns have a way lower accessibility index that the top 25%.
  • TAX has a wide value range, ranging from 187 all the way to 711. The difference between 0-50th percentile is not that big, but there's a 2x jump to the 75th percentile. Seems like a lot of towns have a low tax rate, and then a lot of towns (but less, the top 25%) have a high tax rate. As will be seen later, this column has a bimodal distribution representing this.
  • PTRATIO doesn't have a wide range, and seems to have an outlier in the minimum. The difference between the minimum and the 25th percentile is bigger than between the max and the 25th. The low outlier probably affects the mean and std, but it shouldn't be a low enough value to drastically affect the distribution. Because of this, the distribution is more than likely negatively skewed. Most towns have a high pupil-teacher ratio, with a few outliers in the low side (and in general a pretty similar range when taking all towns into account).
  • LSTAT seems to have outliers in the maximum: the 75th percentile is 16.95% of lower status, while the max is 37.97%. This outlier affects the std and mean heavily, as well as the range. The distribution seems to have most (75% atleast) of the values between 1.73% and 16.95%, but the outliers cause it to go all the way until 37.97%; this column's distribution is positively skewed.
  • MEDV: Finally, the median values of homes. This column also seems to have high outliers: the lowest 75% ranges from 5k dollars to 25k dollars, but then the maximum duplicates the 75th percentile and is at 50k dollars. This is a big enough outlier to affect the std and mean of the column. There is also an outlier in the minimum value: 5k dollars jumps to 17k dollars in the 25th percentile. Despite these outliers, the IQR is not that big (25k at 75th percentile and 17k at 25th). This distribution probably has most values packed in the middle (this IQR range) with a few outliers in both extremes. Most towns have a similar, middle range home value, with a few towns having very cheap house values and others having very expensive values.

We have seen that the variables LSTAT and RM have a linear relationship with the dependent variable MEDV. Also, there are significant relationships among a few independent variables, which is not desirable for a linear regression model. Let's first split the dataset.

Next, we will check the multicollinearity in the train dataset.

Check for Multicollinearity¶

We will use the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF), to check if there is multicollinearity in the data.

Features having a VIF score > 5 will be dropped/treated till all the features have a VIF score < 5

In [22]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# function to check VIF
def checking_vif(train):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = train.columns

    # calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(train.values, i) for i in range(len(train.columns))
    ]
    return vif


print(checking_vif(X_train))

Observations:

  • Adjusted R-squared is lower than R-squared, there are probably some insignificant variables that we should drop.
  • The adjusted R-squared is 0.761, it is probably possible to get a better fit than this (since it can go all the way to 1).
  • If we check the p value and the confidence intervals, we can conclude that:
    • CRIM, CHAS, NOX, RM, DIS, RAD, PTRATIO and LSTAT have a p-value < 0.05. If our Ho is that our feature is not significant, then we can reject this Ho, thus this features are significant to predicting our dependent variable MEDV_log.
      • ZN, INDUS and AGE have a p-value greater than 0.05. Thus we fail to reject Ho, which means these variables are not significant for predicting our dependent variable MEDV_log and should be dropped.
  • The standard error for CRIM, ZN, INDUS, CHAS, RM, AGE, DIS, RAD, PTRATIO and LSTAT is very low (<0.1), the lower the std error, the more accurate the coeficients.
  • The Confidence Intervals let us know where the coefficients will fall 95% of the time. For our significant variables:
    • The CRIM coefficient will fall in between -0.016 and -0.009 95% of the time.
    • The CHAS coefficent will fall between 0.043 and 0.196 95% of the time.
    • The NOX coefficient will fall between -1.427 and -0.692 95% of the time.
    • The RM coefficient will fall between 0.012 and 0.094 95% of the time.
    • The DIS coefficent will fall between -0.071 and -0.03 95% of the time.
    • The RAD coefficient will fall between 0.004 and 0.012 95% of the time.
    • The PTRATIO coefficient will fall between -0.059 and -0.032 95% of the time.
    • The LSTAT coefficient will fall between -0.035 and -0.025 95% of the time.

Question 6: Drop insignificant variables from the above model and create the regression model again. (2 Marks)¶

Examining the significance of the model¶

It is not enough to fit a multiple regression model to the data, it is necessary to check whether all the regression coefficients are significant or not. Significance here means whether the population regression parameters are significantly different from zero.

From the above it may be noted that the regression coefficients corresponding to ZN, AGE, and INDUS are not statistically significant at level α = 0.05. In other words, the regression coefficients corresponding to these three are not significantly different from 0 in the population. Hence, we will eliminate the three features and create a new model.

Now, we will check the linear regression assumptions.

Check the below linear regression assumptions¶

  1. Mean of residuals should be 0
  2. No Heteroscedasticity
  3. Linearity of variables
  4. Normality of error terms

Question 7: Write the code to check the above linear regression assumptions and provide insights. (4 Marks)¶

Check for mean residuals¶

In [31]:
residuals = model2.resid
residuals.mean()
Out[31]:
-3.723951467344381e-15

Observations:

  • A linear regression assumption is that the mean of the residuals should be 0. Here, the mean of residuals is extremely close to 0, so the assumption is satisfied.

Check for homoscedasticity¶

  • Homoscedasticity - If the residuals are symmetrically distributed across the regression line, then the data is said to homoscedastic.

  • Heteroscedasticity - If the residuals are not symmetrically distributed across the regression line, then the data is said to be heteroscedastic. In this case, the residuals can form a funnel shape or any other non-symmetrical shape.

  • We'll use Goldfeldquandt Test to test the following hypothesis with alpha = 0.05:

    • Null hypothesis: Residuals are homoscedastic
    • Alternate hypothesis: Residuals have heteroscedastic
In [32]:
from statsmodels.stats.diagnostic import het_white
from statsmodels.compat import lzip
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
In [34]:
name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(y_train, X_train)
lzip(name, test)
Out[34]:
[('F statistic', 1.0835082923425285), ('p-value', 0.3019012006766869)]

Observations:

  • The p-value is significantly greater than 0.05, therefore we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This means that the residuals are not heteroscedastic, meeting another assumption.

Linearity of variables¶

It states that the predictor variables must have a linear relation with the dependent variable.

To test the assumption, we'll plot residuals and fitted values on a plot and ensure that residuals do not form a strong pattern. They should be randomly and uniformly scattered on the x-axis.

In [36]:
# predicted values
fitted = model2.fittedvalues

# sns.set_style("whitegrid")

plt.xlabel("Fitted Values")
plt.ylabel("Residual")
plt.title("Residual PLOT")
plt.show()

Observations:

  • There should be no clear pattern in the residuals vs fitted values.
  • As we can see, there is no clear pattern. A lot of values are scattered randomly.
  • Therefore, the linearity assumption is satisfied.

Check the performance of the model on the train and test data set¶

Question 8: Write your observations by comparing model performance of train and test dataset (2 Marks)¶

In [38]:
# RMSE
def rmse(predictions, targets):
    return np.sqrt(((targets - predictions) ** 2).mean())


# MAPE
def mape(predictions, targets):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)) / targets) * 100


# MAE
def mae(predictions, targets):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)))


# Model Performance on test and train data
def model_pref(olsmodel, x_train, x_test):

    # In-sample Prediction
    y_pred_train = olsmodel.predict(x_train)
    y_observed_train = y_train

    # Prediction on test data
    y_pred_test = olsmodel.predict(x_test)
    y_observed_test = y_test

    print(
        pd.DataFrame(
            {
                "Data": ["Train", "Test"],
                "RMSE": [
                    rmse(y_pred_train, y_observed_train),
                    rmse(y_pred_test, y_observed_test),
                ],
                "MAE": [
                    mae(y_pred_train, y_observed_train),
                    mae(y_pred_test, y_observed_test),
                ],
                "MAPE": [
                    mape(y_pred_train, y_observed_train),
                    mape(y_pred_test, y_observed_test),
                ],
            }
        )
    )


# Checking model performance
model_pref(model2, X_train, X_test)  

    Data      RMSE       MAE      MAPE
0  Train  0.195504  0.143686  4.981813
1   Test  0.198045  0.151284  5.257965

Observations:

  • The RMSE on the test set is almost identical to that on the training set, which is what we want.
  • The MAE and MAPE on the test set have a bigger difference to the ones on the train set, still not a big difference and similar enough.
  • Our model seems to be generalizing really well, as the performance on test set yields similar results to training sets. If it was overfitting the difference would be bigger since it wouldn't generalize enough but fit the traiing set only. It is not underfitting error.
  • The error on the test set is over 5.25%, we can try reducing it.

Question 11: Write the conclusions and business recommendations derived from the model. (5 Marks)¶

Conclusions:

  • We analyzed which variables had high correlation as to avoid multicollinearity.
    • At first, we evaluated the correlation matrix. But as that wasn't enough, we checked the relation between significantly (>0.7) correlated variables. This let us know if there was a true relation or if outliers where affecting the correlation values.
    • After this, we used Variance Inflation Factor to drop columns which would cause high multicollinearity. We have to drop these columns (in this case, TAX) as to not undermine the significance of other independent variables when we create our predictor.
  • We created a starting Linear Regression Model as to analyze the R squared, coefficient intervals and p values.
    • The lower adjusted r squared value let us know that there were some insignificant variables.
    • P-value analysis let us do a hypothesis test to check which values had high significance in the model. This allowed us to drop insignificant variables: ZN, AGE, and INDUS.
    • We were able to see where the coefficients would fall 95% of the time.
  • We tested to observe if our model meet the linear regression assumptions.
    • Thanks to previous testing, it didn't have multicollinearity.
    • The mean of residuals was approximately 0, meeting that assumption.
    • We did a hypothesis test to check if there was any heterostadicity and there wasn't, meeting that assumption.
    • Variables had linearity. We observed this by plotting Residuals vs fitted values.
    • The residuals had a normal distribution.
  • Since our model met all assumptions, we did cross validation for perfomance assesment
    • The RMSE, MAE, MAPE, r^2 values where close between training set and validation set, which means our model was just right (neither underfitted or overfitted).
    • However, the R-squared values where 0.729 on validation. This could be significantly improved to better explain our dependent variable's variation. *Finally, we obtained the following linear equation: $$log(Price)=4.64-0.125Crim + 0.119CHAS - 1.05NOX + 0.05Rm - 0.044DIS + 0.007RAD - 0.0485PTRATIO - 0.029LSTAT$$

Recommendations:

  • As we can see, reducing per capita crime rate in a town will have a positive effect in Median Household value in this same town. For every reduced crime rate per capita unit, the log of the median value will increase 0.125 units (and the units are in 1000 dollars).
  • The Charles River Dummy Variable has a positive effect on price. However, this can only be 0 or 1. If town tract bounds river, Median household value will increase.
  • Nitric Oxides concentration has a negative effect on a town's median household value. For every NOX unit, this price decreases by over 1 unit. However, NOX values are usually below 1. It seems that, if you want a cheaper house, go to towns with higher air pollution (as higher air pollution usually implies higher NOX).
  • Every room per household increases the median household price in a town by 0.05 units. If your houses on average have more rooms, price will be higher. If you want a cheaper household, less rooms might be what you want to look out for.
  • The farther away your house is from Boston Employment Centers, the cheaper it will be. Living in a town with a lot of close employment centers will increase its price.
  • The index of accessibility to radial highways does increase the median household value, but its effect in this model isn't as big as some of the other variables.
  • Surprisingly, the higher the pupil-teacher ration is in a town, the cheaper the houses will be. Towns with a high ratio could be a good option if you are looking to save money on your household.
  • If you want a cheaper household, you can go to a town where the % of low status citizens is higher. This of course has other drawbacks you would need to consider.
